00 million of trades at net first-day losses to Disfavored Portfolios.</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Statistically, the probability that these diffe=
rences in first-day returns occurred by random chance is less than one in o=
ne trillion.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CFa=
vored Portfolios=E2=80=9D here means Macro Opps; =E2=80=9CDisfavored Portfo=
lios=E2=80=9D means Core and Core Plus.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It =
is a strange sort of cherry-picking=3F =E2=80=9CThe probability that these =
differences =E2=80=A6=C2=A0occurred by random chance=E2=80=9D is low, but t=
he two strategies were=C2=A0<em>different</em>, so the null hypothesis is n=
ot really =E2=80=9Che allocated trades to them randomly.=E2=80=9D And neith=
er of these strategies was really a day-trading strategy: These positions w=
ere generally held for a while, so it=E2=80=99s not clear how much the firs=
t-day gains mattered. The SEC says:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">Although these first-day gains and losses were primarily unrealized (i=
.e., the positions remained open rather than being sold off at the end of =
the day), they nonetheless benefitted Favored Portfolios and disadvantaged =
Disfavored Portfolios because they frequently permitted Favored Portfolios =
to end the day at a gain, and starting a trading position with a gain rathe=
r than a loss ultimately increased the likelihood of Favored Portfolios=E2=
=80=99 successful performance.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>Also Leech had personal money in both funds, though he increased his perso=
nal allocation to Macro Opps and decreased his allocation to Core and Core =
Plus over this period.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Which was a mi=
stake.=C2=A0Macro Opps did=C2=A0not=C2=A0do particularly well during this p=
eriod: It was down a little bit in 2021, and down 21% in 2022.=C2=A0Clients=
 were not impressed.=C2=A0From the indictment:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">Between 2021 and October 2023, S. KENNETH LEECH II, the def=
endant, made a seriesof poor investment decisions that disproportionately a=
ffected Macro Opps, causing significant losses in the fund that led LEECH t=
o seek to improve its performance, even at the expense of clients in the Co=
re Strategies:</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Between 2021 and 2023, LEECH=
 made a series of investment decisions that led to losses across the portfo=
lios he managed, including a large position in Russian debt that was nearly=
 wiped out soon after Russia invaded Ukraine in early 2022 and a significan=
t investment in Credit Suisse debt that also lost all value when Credit Sui=
sse collapsed in early 2023. Although those losses affected many of WAMCO's=
 strategies, including the Core Strategies, they caused particularly acute =
problems for Macro Opps, in large part because Macro Opps had more exposure=
 to some of the losing investments. Over the period described above, the as=
sets under management for Macro Opps fell by approximately 80%, dropping to=
 a low of under $3 billion.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This severe dro=
p in the value of Macro Opps-which LEECH had advertised as reflecting what =
he claimed were WAMCO's best ideas-caused LEECH and the Macro Opps team to =
pay particularly close attention to improving the daily performance of that=
 strategy. During this time of extreme drawdowns in Macro Opps, WAMCO and L=
EECH engaged in a Macro Opps =E2=80=9Cretention campaign=E2=80=9D to convin=
ce clients to keep their investments in Macro Opps. WAMCO attempted to conv=
ince its clients to stay invested in Macro Opps by claiming that Macro Opps=
 typically recovered quickly after suffering losses.</p></blockquote><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know that the Macro Opps investors <=
em>felt=C2=A0</em>like they were the favored funds. The theory here is some=
thing like =E2=80=9CLeech made bad long-term investment decisions for Macro=
 Opps, but tried to partially make up for it by allocating the trades with =
one-day gains to Macro Opps.=E2=80=9D The one-day gains did not make up for=
 the bad decisions. I feel like if I were running two investment funds, and=
 one was melting down, I would probably favor the=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>=
one=3F</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway I suppose the useful lesson h=
ere is =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t wait until the end of the day to allocate you=
r trades, because even if you do it honestly it=E2=80=99s gonna look bad.=
=E2=80=9D The SEC quotes Wamco compliance trainings:</p><blockquote><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a June 2018 compliance training, Western Asset=E2=
=80=99s Chief Compliance Officer (=E2=80=9CCCO=E2=80=9D) warned employees t=
o finalize =E2=80=9Callocations and the trade ticket promptly after the tra=
de execution.=E2=80=9D He explained, =E2=80=9Cthis is another thing that we=
 know that the regulators are doing, they=E2=80=99re looking at time stamps=
. So, if they get a sense that you executed first thing in the morning, bu=
t we didn=E2=80=99t allocate until the end of the day, they may come to us =
=E2=80=A6 and wonder =E2=80=A6 =E2=80=98you only allocated after you saw wh=
at the market did.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In=
 a training conducted in June 2022, Western Asset=E2=80=99s CCO stated that=
 in going through the daily trade process, employees should finalize trade =
allocations =E2=80=9Cpromptly after the trade is executed.=E2=80=9D Then he=
 described the following as a =E2=80=9Cbad facts scenario=E2=80=9D: =E2=80=
=9CLet=E2=80=99s say you execute that trade at 8am, the market moves, you p=
ost that allocation at noon.=E2=80=9D He further explains, =E2=80=9Chow do =
we know whether that allocation posted at noon was influenced by the market=
 move=3F How do we know that you =E2=80=A6 saw the market move in a particu=
lar way, and you didn=E2=80=99t tweak that allocation with that knowledge i=
n your mind=3F How do you prove it=3F=E2=80=9D Further, he said =E2=80=9Cth=
e risk that we have is longer the longer the trade sits between execution a=
nd posting.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the ol=
den days, when everyone did trades by phone and wrote up paper tickets at t=
he end of the day, it would be reasonable to say =E2=80=9Cwe allocate our t=
rades at the end of the day and if we do a little cherry-picking, well, who=
 can prove it=3F=E2=80=9D Whereas in the modern world where =E2=80=9CWester=
n Asset=E2=80=99s electronic trade management system allowed portfolio mana=
gers to prepare draft trade tickets and specify an allocation instruction e=
ven before placing a trade,=E2=80=9D you look a bit like a dinosaur doing a=
ll of your trades by phone and making your assistant chase you for allocati=
ons at the end of the day. And the burden might be on you to prove that you=
=C2=A0<em>weren=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>cherry-picking.</p><table class=3D"live=
